  "prompt": "What is the best way to simplify [math]\\frac{x-\\frac{1}{x}}{1+\\frac{1}{x}}[/math] where defined?",
  "response": "To simplify the expression \\(\\frac{x-\\frac{1}{x}}{1+\\frac{1}{x}}\\), we can follow these steps:\n\n1. **Rewrite the fraction**: Combine the terms involving \\(x\\) and \\(\\frac{1}{x}\\) under a common denominator.\n\n\\[ \\frac{x - \\frac{1}{x}}{1 + \\frac{1}{x}} \\]\n\n2. **Combine the terms in the numerator**: Take the common denominator of the terms in the numerator.\n\n\\[ x - \\frac{1}{x} = \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x} \\]\n\nSo the numerator becomes:\n\n\\[ \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x} \\]\n\n3. **Combine the terms in the denominator**: Similarly, take the common denominator of the terms in the denominator.\n\n\\[ 1 + \\frac{1}{x} = \\frac{x + 1}{x} \\]\n\nSo the denominator becomes:\n\n\\[ \\frac{x + 1}{x} \\]\n\n4. **Rewrite the entire expression**: Now substitute these simplified fractions into the original expression.\n\n\\[ \\frac{\\frac{x^2 - 1}{x}}{\\frac{x + 1}{x}} \\]\n\n5. **Simplify the complex fraction**: Cancel the common \\(\\frac{1}{x}\\) terms from the numerator and denominator.\n\n\\[ \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x} \\div \\frac{x + 1}{x} = \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x} \\times \\frac{x}{x + 1} \\]\n\n\\[ = \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x + 1} \\]\n\n6. **Factor the numerator**: Notice that \\(x^2 - 1\\) is a difference of squares which can be factored.\n\n\\[ x^2 - 1 = (x - 1)(x + 1) \\]\n\nSo the fraction becomes:\n\n\\[ \\frac{(x - 1)(x + 1)}{x + 1} \\]\n\n7. **Cancel common terms**: If \\(x + 1 \\neq 0\\),\n\n\\[ \\frac{(x - 1)(x + 1)}{x + 1} = x - 1 \\]\n\nTherefore, the simplified form of the expression \\(\\frac{x-\\frac{1}{x}}{1+\\frac{1}{x}}\\) is:\n\n\\[ x - 1 \\]\n\n**Conditions**: \\(x \\neq -1\\) because the expression would be undefined due to division by zero.\n\nSo the final simplified expression is \\(x - 1\\), valid for \\(x \\neq -1\\).",
